               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261207-7-person145">
                  FRANCIS 
                  COOKSON
               <interp inst="t18261207-7-person145" type="surname" value="COOKSON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261207-7-person145" type="given" value="FRANCIS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261207-7-person145" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am in the employ of Mr. William Row, who has other partners. On Monday last I found a martin's-skin at the bottom of the warehouse-stairs - Hazle picked it up, and the men were collected to be searched.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18261207-7-person146">
                  THOMAS 
                  HAZLE
               <interp inst="t18261207-7-person146" type="surname" value="HAZLE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261207-7-person146" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18261207-7-person146" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am foreman to Messrs. Row and Co. On the 4th of December, Cookson showed me where<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182612070009"></xptr>he had found this skin; I called the men together, there were six in all, the prisoner was one of them - he seemed reluctant to come forward, and therefore I searched him first and found eleven martins'-skins stuffed into his waistcoat and trousers - they were about half way into his trousers, but his apron quite concealed them - he said it was his first offence, and he hoped I would look over it; he has been three years in our service; we have missed property for some years past - they are worth 4s. or 5s.(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
